It‚Äôs delicious, well balanced garlic pepper.I have grabbed it for everything so far: most recently-- to doctor up a store bought pizza, and as a flavoring for a pork tenderloin.

This is a straight forward and easy to use infrared thermometer. It comes ready to go with batteries already installed. It fits comfortably in your hand like a remote control. There is an option for voice readings, but it's easy to turn that off. The directions say you have to be 1 - 3 cm from the forehead to get an accurate reading. My initial readings varied widely, but once I started paying attention to the distance, the readings were more accurate. The temperature readings that I took of the air in the room were spot on with what my thermostat read.

*I purchased this at a reduced price for the purpose of trying out & reviewing. My thoughts & opinions are my own.

For some reason I had thought these would be small jars.... they are HUGE !! I'm sharing the jars around. So many things are better with ginger and the grated texture could be used many ways including sushi and hot or ice tea.. ice cream... asian slaw... So many options. Good thing cause there's so much of it! There were 6 giant jars (I'm sharing with every one I know). Came in a separated cardboard crate type box. All the jars were solidly sealed. The expire date is posted as 2/2021. I really love there are NO artificial ingredients! I recently found out that most commercial pickled ginger contains aspartame - which I refuse to eat. This ginger does NOT - organic ginger, cane sugar, water, rice vinegar, salt and citric acid. Perfect. I never hesitate to update my reviews should new info seem useful and I hope my review was helpful to you!

This is a 4.23 ounce bag of classical mixed dried mushrooms (suillus granulatus, shiitake slices, wood ear, and oyster mushrooms). This is a product of China.

Per the instructions, I soaked them in warm water for 30 minutes until soft and then strained them through a coffee filter reserving some liquid. I then rinsed the mushrooms under cold water and added them to my rice dish. They gave the dish texture but not much flavor--even with the juices. However, I find that is typical of all mushrooms whether dried or fresh.

Note that there is a freshness packet in the bag (desiccant) that has to be thrown out. Be sure not to eat that.

The current price of $17.59 ($21.99 minus 20%) comes to $4.16 per ounce.

I like Kombucha but sometimes the flavor is a little off putting, or the vinegar bite is too strong, so I was curious how a powdered instant version would fare. My go to flavor is Lemon Ginger, so I figured if I were to try an instant version it would make sense to try a familiar flavor.

Directions say to add one packet to 14-16 ounces of still water or carbonated water. I currently do not have any carbonated, so I used filtered water. It mixes very easily, and has a pleasant taste. It isnt too sweet for me. I can taste lemon first with a light ginger finish. It is nice tasting and refreshing. Love loading my cup with ice and sipping on it. I actually like it better than most bottled Kombucha because it doesnt have any of that apple cider taste. If that is what draws you to Kombucha, then you will miss it here.

I would consider this again

I bought two of these. They are absolute garbage. They are cast aluminum products instead of CNC milled parts from aircraft grade aluminum and as such they are very weak. These are cheap pedals that will require regular disassembly, cleaning, and greasing to stay functional.

Unlike most modern pedals (including other VPs), these employ a rather narrow bushing for the inner and a small bearing for the outer. The "tightness" other reviewers have commented on is part of the design and will subside as the pedals break in ... and wear out. Further, there is no seal on the inner. There was no anti-seize compound on the outer shaft end aluminum-to-aluminum cap; that should be added to ensure they don't fuse due to oxidation.

At $15/pair, they're passable in a pinch but they'll have a shorter lifespan, won't function as well as a full bearing pedal, and will require a more frequent maintenance cycle.

I've ordered Kauai coffee from Amazon before with no issues, however the latest order I just received is defective or an imposter. The first indication of a possible problem is the pod looks different than the order I received the previous month - the pod doesn't contain any labeling indicating it's the vanilla macadamia nut flavor, it has a different color ring on the top, and the band underneath is brown (instead of white). It also isn't recognized as a compatible K-Cup in my Keurig brewer. Again, I had no problems with the order I received last month. I called the Kauai Coffee company and they told me the coffee ordered through Amazon is either through a 3rd party seller or their parent company, and may contain only 10% Kauai coffee. She recommended I purchase directly from their website to ensure we receive 100% Kauai coffee direct from the farm. I will be ordering direct from now on.

This is a subtle but nice jasmine tea with a hint of jasmine flavor. There are 16 ounces of loose leaf organic tea in the box. The fragrance when dry and the flavor when brewed is subtle but good.

Buying the Gotrax XR Elite Electric Scooter was a dumb and expensive decision. It was a great scooter to for getting back and forth to elementary school while it lasted. But one false move (hit a curb) and the front fork bent. I did not consider how important replacement parts would be when I purchased this scooter. Unfortunately, the manufacturer doesn't sell parts, but they did offer a slight discount for me to purchase a brand new one. I guess the people at GoTrax think we all have hundreds of dollars to spend on a new scooter every few months. Clearly, they aren't thinking about engineering for mass production.
Right now my kid's scooter is at my friend's bodyshop - maybe they can fix it. If not, I think an e-bike would be a more durable and a safer option. And I will be sure that e-bike has replacement parts available.
Think seriously about buying a Gotrax product as it can very easily become an expensive paperweight in your garage.

Any drink that is made from herbal ingredients is a tisane and not a tea. Tea only comes from two main varieties of the camellia sinensis evergreen. This is both a tea and a tisane as it has both ingredients. There is one resealable pouch of 22 tea bags. The organic ingredients are decaf green tea with spearmint and peppermint leaves.

I brewed this with 10 ounces of boiling water and steeped it for 10 minutes as recommended. The tea is fresh, smells "minty" fragrant, and brews to a clear caramel hue. The flavor is super minty but balanced. It is absolutely delicious. What is interesting is that green tea is usually not brewed with boiling water because it creates a bitter brew but herbal ingredients are brewed that way. Nevertheless, there is no bitterness in this tea.

The current price of $10.99 comes to a very reasonable $.50 cents per bag.

Order this radiator SPECIFICALLY because the photo in this add shows evenly spaced (not offset) fans with no louvers in the shroud. What came is the same that everyone else sells, louvered and offset mounted fans. The louvers cause reversion through the fan (circular air flow instead of forced-through), reducing cooling. Also, the overflow nipple is on the wrong side. Overflow is on drivers side, but this one is on pass, so you have bend hose around and when it gets hot, the hose collapses and pinches itself, closing off the overflow until pressure blows past, then it doesn't suck the coolant back up when it cools (like overflows should work). Just a fail. Skip this one.

There are two food-grade silicone teethers in this package that look like a helmet to me. The silicone is super soft. First of all, the flavor is good, as it tastes like peanut butter. However, I suggest that anyone wanting to purchase this, please research the differences between "Digestibility Corrected Facts" and "Nutrition Facts."
As most will know, 28 calories for 2 Tbsp of peanut butter (the digestibility corrected number) is extremely low and really too good to be true. Without this correction it's actually 200 calories for 2 Tbsp. This is actually a bit more than regular peanut butter. I'm not saying this is false advertising, but there's more to it than just the giant "28" on the label.

Also, suggest looking up "adverse reactions to malabsorption food products." Not going into detail here, so just research it.

As Harken well knows, the industry standard is to identify rings of this type by the diameter of the circumference groove NOT the center hole. Compare the Notch and Tylaska rings in the photos. Notice that the much larger Tylaska is identified as a 26; whereas the Harken is labelled as a 28. The Notch ring is fully identified as 38 x 28. Also notice the edges of the circumference groove. The Notch groove edges are properly machined. The Harken edges are sharp enough to sever a line under load. In arboriculture, that could prove fatal. The other two manufacturers give clear load ratings for their rings. Harken offers none. This is garbage! I immediately attempted to return the ring only to discover that it is not returnable, at all. Notch and Tylaska both have generous return policies. You might also notice that the Harken reviews show significant negative ratings, yet none of the negative reviews can be accessed.
